SIMPLE: ite
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: -ite
<hw>-ite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <ety>[From Gr. <?/, <?/.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>A suffix denoting <sig>one of a party</sig>, a <sig>sympathizer
with</sig> or <sig>adherent of</sig>, and the like, and frequently used
in ridicule; <as>as, a Miller<ex>ite</ex>; a
Bentham<ex>ite</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A suffix used in naming minerals; <as>as,
chlor<ex>ite</ex>, from its characteristic green color; bar<ex>ite</ex>,
from its heaviness; graph<ex>ite</ex>, from its use in
writing.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A suffix used to denote the salts
formed from those acids whose names end in <xex>-ous</xex>; <as>as,
sulph<ex>ite</ex>, from sulphur<ex>ous</ex>; nitr<ex>ite</ex>, from
nitr<ex>ous</ex> acid, etc.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Itelmen</ent>⟦br⟧
